# =========================================================================
# UdaanSetu.AI - Firebase Configuration Template & Setup Guide
# =========================================================================
# Copy this file to `.env` or `.env.local` inside the `frontend` folder 
# and fill in your actual Firebase project values.
# =========================================================================

NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project-id.firebaseapp.com
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project-id.firebasestorage.app
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=1234567890
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID=1:1234567890:web:abcdef1234567890abcdef12

# =========================================================================
# 🛠️ STEP-BY-STEP FIREBASE SETUP INSTRUCTIONS
# =========================================================================

# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1️⃣ HOW TO CREATE A FIREBASE PROJECT
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Open your browser and navigate to the Firebase Console:
#    👉 https://console.firebase.google.com/
# 2. Sign in with your Google Account.
# 3. Click on the "Add project" button (or "Create a project").
# 4. Enter your project name (e.g., "UdaanSetu-AI") and click "Continue".
# 5. Choose whether to enable Google Analytics for the project (optional) 
#    and click "Continue" or "Create project".
# 6. Wait for the project creation process to finish, then click "Continue".

# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2️⃣ HOW TO CREATE A WEB APP (Get Config Keys)
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. In your Firebase Project overview dashboard, click the "Web" icon 
#    (looks like `</>`) to register a new web application.
# 2. Enter an App Nickname (e.g., "UdaanSetu Web Client").
# 3. (Optional) Leave "Also set up Firebase Hosting..." unchecked and click 
#    "Register app".
# 4. Firebase will display a code snippet containing the `firebaseConfig` object.
# 5. Extract and copy the credentials:
#    - `apiKey`           -> maps to `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY`
#    - `authDomain`       -> maps to `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN`
#    - `projectId`        -> maps to `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID`
#    - `storageBucket`    -> maps to `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET`
#    - `messagingSenderId`-> maps to `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID`
#    - `appId`            -> maps to `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID`
# 6. Paste these values into your local `.env` or `.env.local` file.

# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3️⃣ HOW TO ENABLE FIREBASE AUTHENTICATION
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. In the Firebase Console left-side navigation bar, click on "Build" > "Authentication".
# 2. Click "Get started".
# 3. Under the "Sign-in method" tab, configure the following providers:
#
#    A. Email/Password:
#       - Click on "Email/Password".
#       - Toggle the first switch to "Enable" (allow user sign-in with email & password).
#       - Click "Save".
#
#    B. Google Sign-In (Optional but recommended):
#       - Click "Add new provider" and select "Google".
#       - Toggle the "Enable" switch.
#       - Select a project support email from the dropdown menu.
#       - Click "Save".
#
# 4. The application is now configured to handle authentication flows.

# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4️⃣ HOW TO CREATE & CONFIG FIRESTORE DATABASE
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. In the Firebase Console left-side navigation bar, click on "Build" > "Firestore Database".
# 2. Click on the "Create database" button.
# 3. Configure Database Settings:
#    - Location: Choose a location close to your users (e.g., `asia-south1` for India).
#    - Click "Next".
# 4. Security Rules Mode:
#    - Select "Start in production mode" (this keeps your database secure by default).
#    - Click "Create".
# 5. Your Firestore instance will be initialized.

# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5️⃣ HOW TO ADD SECURITY RULES FOR FIRESTORE
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. In the Firestore Database section, click on the "Rules" tab at the top.
# 2. You will see the default rules editor.
# 3. Open the `firebase-rules.txt` file located in `frontend/DOC/firebase-rules.txt`.
# 4. Copy the entire content of that file.
# 5. Paste it into the Firebase Console rules editor, replacing the existing content.
# 6. Click the "Publish" button to deploy the rules.
#
# 💡 Note: These rules restrict read/write access so that authenticated users
#    can only read and write their own profile and assessment documents.
# =========================================================================
